Date:5/10/2004 1:47:44 PM
From:Bridge Player
IMO the sharp sell-off in REITS may be overdone. I just ran across Amerivest
Properties Inc., symbol AMV. They are an interesting combination of a small,
micro-cap growth company and a high-yield REIT.

http://www.amvproperties.com/company/

Incorporated in Maryland but based in Denver, they own and operate upscale
office properties catering to small businesses, those generally needing less
than 4000 sq. ft. of space. They offer amenities such as key-card entry, shared
conference space with the latest technology available at no charge,
individually tenant-controlled heat and air conditioning, etc. They own
properties in Texas, Arizona, and Colorado.

Started in about 1996, they are still small but steadily growing. Their sales,
assets, and dividends have grown steadily since founding, and their current
dividend of 0.52 annually offers a yield of over 9% at the closing price on
Friday 5/7 of $5.59. ($5.52 as I write this.) The price range since 1995 is
about 3 to 7.

Browse their web site a bit and see what you think. I'm not sure if this could
truly be considered a "value" stock, but I like their track record, the tenor
of the company's mission statement, and the yield.
